topLevelComment.text:
In your example, the default index page initally used an arrow function but when I create the app it uses:

import React from "react"

export default function Home() {
  return <div>Hello world!</div>
}

Did they change the hello-world starter and why?

replies.text:
@Jakedalus Interesting... I was not able to render any content using documentToReactComponents.  I tried using this community-made package:
https://github.com/connor-baer/rich-text-to-jsx 

Using that, I was able to see all of the content except the image

Try adding this snippet into gatsby-config.js:
require("dotenv").config({
  path: `.env.${process.env.NODE_ENV}`,
})

@Mista Winta does your gatsby-config.js file have both title and author in it for siteMetadata ? That's where the fields are coming from, mine looks like this:

module.exports = {
  /* Your site config here */
  siteMetadata: {
      title: 'Full-Stack Bootcamp!',
      author: 'Mike Harrison'
  },
...

and it worked for me, I was able to access both fields once I had restarted my gatsby server.
